Based on my analysis of your codebase, here's how you can implement a centralized documentation system that works both as a standalone page and in modal views throughout your app:

## Design Architecture

### 1. **Create a Centralized Documentation Content Structure**

First, create a documentation content system with structured data:

```typescript
// src/types/docs.ts
export interface DocSection {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  description: string;
  content: string; // Markdown or HTML content
  category: 'getting-started' | 'features' | 'workflows' | 'integrations' | 'analytics' | 'advanced';
  tags?: string[];
  relatedSections?: string[];
}

export interface DocCategory {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  icon?: string;
  sections: DocSection[];
}
```

### 2. **Create a Documentation Store** (Nanostore pattern you're already using)

```typescript
// src/stores/docsStore.ts
import { atom } from 'nanostores';
import type { DocSection } from '@/types/docs';

export interface DocsModalState {
  isOpen: boolean;
  sectionId?: string;
  scrollToSection?: string;
}

export const docsModalState = atom<DocsModalState>({
  isOpen: false,
});

export const openDocsModal = (sectionId?: string) => {
  docsModalState.set({
    isOpen: true,
    sectionId,
  });
};

export const closeDocsModal = () => {
  docsModalState.set({
    isOpen: false,
    sectionId: undefined,
  });
};

// Active section for the full docs page
export const activeDocSection = atom<string | undefined>(undefined);
```

### 3. **Create a Reusable Documentation Content Component**

```vue
<!-- src/components/vue/docs/DocContent.vue -->
<template>
  <div class="doc-content">
    <!-- Tab Navigation (if showing all categories) -->
    <div v-if="!singleSection" class="doc-tabs">
      <button
        v-for="category in categories"
        :key="category.id"
        @click="activeCategory = category.id"
        :class="{ 'active': activeCategory === category.id }"
      >
        {{ category.label }}
      </button>
    </div>

    <!-- Content Area -->
    <div class="doc-sections">
      <template v-if="singleSection">
        <!-- Single section for modal -->
        <DocSection :section="currentSection" />
      </template>
      <template v-else>
        <!-- All sections for full page with categories -->
        <div
          v-for="section in filteredSections"
          :key="section.id"
          :id="section.id"
          class="doc-section"
        >
          <DocSection :section="section" />
        </div>
      </template>
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { computed, ref, watch } from 'vue';
import type { DocSection, DocCategory } from '@/types/docs';
import DocSection from './DocSection.vue';

const props = defineProps<{
  sectionId?: string; // If provided, show only this section
  categories: DocCategory[];
}>();

const activeCategory = ref(props.categories[0]?.id);
const singleSection = computed(() => !!props.sectionId);

const currentSection = computed(() => {
  if (!props.sectionId) return null;
  return props.categories
    .flatMap(cat => cat.sections)
    .find(section => section.id === props.sectionId);
});

const filteredSections = computed(() => {
  const category = props.categories.find(cat => cat.id === activeCategory.value);
  return category?.sections || [];
});
</script>
```

### 4. **Create a Documentation Modal Component**

```vue
<!-- src/components/vue/modals/DocsModal.vue -->
<template>
  <BaseModal
    v-model:open="isOpen"
    :close-on-click-outside="true"
    :close-on-escape="true"
    content-class="w-full max-w-4xl"
  >
    <template #title>
      <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold">Documentation</h3>
        <button @click="closeModal" class="text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-600">
          <Icon name="mdi:close" class="w-6 h-6" />
        </button>
      </div>
    </template>

    <template #content>
      <DocContent
        :section-id="modalState.sectionId"
        :categories="docCategories"
      />
    </template>

    <template #footer>
      <div class="px-6 py-4 flex justify-between items-center">
        <a
          :href="`/dashboard/docs${modalState.sectionId ? `#${modalState.sectionId}` : ''}`"
          class="text-primary-600 hover:text-primary-700"
        >
          View full documentation 
        </a>
        <OutlineButton @click="closeModal" text="Close" />
      </div>
    </template>
  </BaseModal>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { computed } from 'vue';
import { useStore } from '@nanostores/vue';
import { docsModalState, closeDocsModal } from '@/stores/docsStore';
import BaseModal from './BaseModal.vue';
import DocContent from '@vue/docs/DocContent.vue';
import { docCategories } from '@/content/docs'; // Your doc data

const modalState = useStore(docsModalState);
const isOpen = computed({
  get: () => modalState.value.isOpen,
  set: (value) => {
    if (!value) closeDocsModal();
  },
});

const closeModal = () => {
  closeDocsModal();
};
</script>
```

### 5. **Full Documentation Page**

```astro
---
// src/pages/dashboard/docs/index.astro
import DashLayout from '@layouts/DashLayout.astro';
import DocsPageView from '@vue/views/docs/DocsPageView.vue';
---

<DashLayout title="Documentation">
  <DocsPageView client:load />
</DashLayout>
```

```vue
<!-- src/components/vue/views/docs/DocsPageView.vue -->
<template>
  <div class="docs-page">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Documentation</h1>
      <DocContent :categories="docCategories" />
    </div>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import DocContent from '@vue/docs/DocContent.vue';
import { docCategories } from '@/content/docs';
</script>
```

### 6. **"Learn More" Button Component**

```vue
<!-- src/components/vue/buttons/LearnMoreButton.vue -->
<template>
  <button
    @click="openDocs"
    class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-primary-600 hover:text-primary-700 transition-colors"
  >
    <Icon name="mdi:information-outline" class="w-4 h-4" />
    <span>{{ text }}</span>
  </button>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { openDocsModal } from '@/stores/docsStore';

const props = defineProps<{
  sectionId: string;
  text?: string;
}>();

const openDocs = () => {
  openDocsModal(props.sectionId);
};
</script>
```

### 7. **Documentation Content Structure**

```typescript
// src/content/docs/index.ts
import type { DocCategory } from '@/types/docs';

export const docCategories: DocCategory[] = [
  {
    id: 'getting-started',
    label: 'Getting Started',
    sections: [
      {
        id: 'welcome',
        title: 'Welcome to Socialaize',
        description: 'Get started with social media management',
        content: `...markdown content...`,
        category: 'getting-started',
      },
      // More sections...
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'workflows',
    label: 'Workflows',
    sections: [
      {
        id: 'workflow-basics',
        title: 'Workflow Basics',
        description: 'Learn how to automate your social media',
        content: `...markdown content...`,
        category: 'workflows',
      },
      // More sections...
    ],
  },
  // More categories...
];
```

### 8. **Usage Throughout Your App**

```vue
<!-- Example: In any feature component -->
<template>
  <div class="feature-section">
    <h3>AI Workflow Automation</h3>
    <p>Automate your posting with AI-powered workflows</p>
    <LearnMoreButton section-id="workflow-basics" text="Learn about workflows" />
  </div>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import LearnMoreButton from '@vue/buttons/LearnMoreButton.vue';
</script>
```

### 9. **Add Modal to Your App Root**

```vue
<!-- Add to your main layout or App.vue -->
<template>
  <!-- Your existing layout -->
  <DocsModal />
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import DocsModal from '@vue/modals/DocsModal.vue';
</script>
```

## Key Benefits of This Architecture

1. **Single Source of Truth**: Documentation content is centralized in one location
2. **Reusable Components**: `DocContent` works in both modal and full-page contexts
3. **Deep Linking**: Full docs page supports URL hash anchors for specific sections
4. **Context-Aware**: Modal can show specific sections relevant to the feature
5. **SEO Friendly**: Full page is crawlable, modal provides quick in-app help
6. **Consistent with Your Stack**: Uses Nanostores (like your other modals), Vue 3, and your existing BaseModal component

This design lets you maintain documentation in one place while providing both standalone documentation pages and contextual help modals throughout your application.

